          "body": "The wall's collapse at the shout (6:20) fulfills precisely what God announced in 6:5, closing the chapter's command-fulfillment arc with exact verbal correspondence. But the narrator does not linger on the miracle of the falling wall — he immediately turns to the ban (*cherem*, 6:17-21), which is the chapter's theologically most demanding material. *Cherem* is the complete consecration of conquered persons and property to YHWH, which in practice means destruction. Jericho is the firstfruits city of the conquest — the first ripe grain of Canaan belongs entirely to YHWH, just as the firstfruits of the harvest belong to the sanctuary (Exodus 23:19; Leviticus 23:10). Nothing may be privatized. The difficulty modern readers feel with this passage is real and must not be suppressed. At minimum, two things must be said. First, *cherem* warfare is the exception, not the rule, in Israel's conquest — subsequent cities are not placed under total ban (Joshua 8:2, 27). Jericho is unique as the firstfruits offering. Second, the theological logic is coherent within the framework of divine ownership of the land: Canaan belongs to YHWH, who dispossesses its occupants not arbitrarily but after centuries of delay (Genesis 15:16; Leviticus 18:24-28). Joshua's warning in 6:18 that taking banned items will 'make the camp of Israel accursed' is borne out immediately in chapter 7 with Achan's sin — the ban's terms are not rhetorical."
